ames><gtr:surname>Hellyer</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=RES-173-27-0045"><gtr:id>ADC1FC8C-1E9A-4009-A047-38F4C4C937D3</gtr:id><gtr:title>Muslim Religious Authority in Western Europe</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-173-27-0045</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>The focus on Muslim communities has changed in popular culture as well as
&lt;br />academic circles in the last few decades: from historical analysis to
&lt;br />contemporary sociological study, and from envisaging them as foreign
&lt;br />communities to investigating them as integral parts of Western societies.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />There has also been an increased interest in the theological underpinnings
&lt;br />of this community; the study of Islam as a religion has become of marked
&lt;br />importance.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />The activity of both of these fields, loosely defined as 'Muslim studies'
&lt;br />and 'Islamic studies' has often been philosophically separate. This study
&lt;br />seeks to investigate how authority is formed in one, due to the importance
&lt;br />of it in the other: how do Muslims construct authority in Islam? What
&lt;br />institutions exist in Muslim European communities already? What do they
&lt;br />focus upon in their usual activities? How have they been constructed? What
&lt;br />moves are underway in different European countries to construct religious
&lt;br />authority? What 'good practice' exists that might be transplantable?
&lt;br />
&lt;br />The focus will be given to Europe, and field research will be carried out
&lt;br />during the fellowship with a view to the published research being
&lt;br />disseminated in 2008.
&lt;br />
